Author::::digitaldr
DateTime::::2016-02-29T15:20:28Z
Interestingly talc can be used in a surgical procedure called pleurodesis which is used to prevent recurrent pneumothorax and malignant pleural effusion caused by mesothelioma. This involves introducing talc into the pleural space - the gap between the lining of the inner chest wall and the lining of the lungs which causes the two layers to be become inflamed to such an extent that they stick to each other thus obliterating the pleural space. No pleural space means there's nowhere for fluid to accumulate (prevents pleural effusion) or air to enter (prevents pneumothorax). As far as I am aware the use of asbestos free talc for pleurodesis has not been shown to increase cancer risk. Might be a different story wrt the ovaries of course.



